[30;1m1245 | [0m[35mcreates a uniform distribution in two parts. The easy part is when the device[0m
[30;1m1246 | [0m[35mis powered, in which case we allocate the blocks linearly, circling the device.[0m
[30;1m1247 | [0m[35mThe harder part is what to do when the device loses power. We can't just[0m
[30;1m1248 | [0m[35mrestart the allocator at the beginning of storage, as this would bias the wear.[0m
[30;1m1249 | [0m[35mInstead, we start the allocator as a random offset every time we mount the[0m
[30;1m1250 | [0m[35mfilesystem. As long as this random offset is uniform, the combined allocation[0m
[30;1m1251 | [0m[35mpattern is also a uniform distribution.[0m

[30;1m595 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m596 | [0m[35mTo avoid a full copy during appends, we can store the data backwards. Appending[0m
[30;1m597 | [0m[35mblocks just requires adding the new block and no other blocks need to be[0m
[30;1m598 | [0m[35mupdated. If we update a block in the middle, we still need to copy the[0m
[30;1m599 | [0m[35mfollowing blocks, but can reuse any blocks before it. Since most file writes[0m
[30;1m600 | [0m[35mare linear, this design gambles that appends are the most common type of data[0m
[30;1m601 | [0m[35mupdate.[0m

[30;1m350 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m351 | [0m[35mSo how do we atomically update our metadata pairs? Atomicity (a type of[0m
[30;1m352 | [0m[35mpower-loss resilience) requires two parts: redundancy and error detection.[0m
[30;1m353 | [0m[35mError detection can be provided with a checksum, and in littlefs's case we[0m
[30;1m354 | [0m[35muse a 32-bit [CRC][wikipedia-crc]. Maintaining redundancy, on the other hand,[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m313[0m[34m of [0m[33m1283[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000600[0m

[30;1m45 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m46 | [0m[35m1. **Power-loss resilience** - On these systems, power can be lost at any time.[0m
[30;1m47 | [0m[35m   If a power loss corrupts any persistent data structures, this can cause the[0m
[30;1m48 | [0m[35m   device to become unrecoverable. An embedded filesystem must be designed to[0m
[30;1m49 | [0m[35m   recover from a power loss during any write operation.[0m

[30;1m38 | [0m[35mTo make the situation more annoying, it's very common for these embedded[0m
[30;1m39 | [0m[35msystems to lose power at any time. Usually, microcontroller code is simple and[0m

[30;1m540 | [0m[35m---[0m
[30;1m541 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m542 | [0m[35mIf we look at metadata pairs and linked-lists of metadata pairs at a high[0m
[30;1m543 | [0m[35mlevel, they have fairly nice runtime costs. Assuming _n_ metadata pairs,[0m
[30;1m544 | [0m[35meach containing _m_ metadata entries, the _lookup_ cost for a specific[0m

[30;1m220 | [0m[35m   Well, almost. The unbounded upwards movement of updates causes some[0m
[30;1m221 | [0m[35m   problems. Because updates to a COW filesystem don't stop until they've[0m
[30;1m222 | [0m[35m   reached the root, an update can cascade into a larger set of writes than[0m

[30;1m139 | [0m[35mAt a high level, littlefs is a block based filesystem that uses small logs to[0m
[30;1m140 | [0m[35mstore metadata and larger copy-on-write (COW) structures to store file data.[0m
[30;1m141 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m142 | [0m[35mIn littlefs, these ingredients form a sort of two-layered cake, with the small[0m
[30;1m143 | [0m[35mlogs (called metadata pairs) providing fast updates to metadata anywhere on[0m
[30;1m144 | [0m[35mstorage, while the COW structures store file data compactly and without any[0m
[30;1m145 | [0m[35mwear amplification cost.[0m

[30;1m190 | [0m[35m1. Each tag contains a valid bit used to indicate if the tag and containing[0m

[30;1m194 | [0m[35m   with the lowest bit in the type field of the CRC tag. This allows[0m
[30;1m195 | [0m[35m   the CRC tag to force the next commit to fail the valid bit test if it[0m
